# User instructions — be short, explicit, copy-pasteable

When you need the user to perform a manual step (run SQL, set an env var,
configure Stripe, click in a dashboard, etc.), follow these rules.

## Format

1. **One numbered list. Keep it under 6 steps.** No prose paragraphs around it.
2. **Every link must be a clickable URL.** Don't say "go to Supabase" — say
   "click [Open Supabase SQL Editor](https://supabase.com/dashboard/project/_/sql/new)".
3. **Anything they need to type or paste must be in a code block** (or a
   `<details>` block linking to the file). No prose with "copy this".
4. **End with one sentence: "What success looks like."** So they know when
   they're done.

## Don't

- Don't reference filenames they have to open ("open `foo.sql` in your
  editor"). Embed the contents inline OR link to GitHub raw, OR provide
  the literal SQL/JSON/text they should paste.
- Don't explain *why* — they don't care while they're doing the task. The
  "why" goes in the commit message and code comments.
- Don't say "easy" or "simple". Just give the steps.
- Don't add "let me know when done" — assume they'll say so.

## Example — bad

> You'll need to run the new Supabase migration so the waitlist table
> exists. Open Supabase, go to SQL Editor, find the file at
> `supabase/migrations/006_ad_waitlist.sql` and run it.

## Example — good

> **Run this SQL in Supabase ([open SQL editor](https://supabase.com/dashboard/project/_/sql/new)):**
>
> ```sql
> -- entire file contents pasted here, ready to copy
> create table if not exists public.ad_waitlist ( ... );
> ```
>
> **Done when:** you see "Success. No rows returned."

## Apply this format every time you need any manual user action

This includes (non-exhaustive): SQL migrations, Vercel env vars, Stripe
dashboard config, DNS changes, Google Cloud / GA / GSC setup, Resend
sender verification, social-image cache busts, Supabase Auth providers,
Supabase Storage policies, anything in a third-party dashboard.
